\begin_layout Subsection
Entering notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To write a melody, click on the partition at the location of the first note.
 Then add a note by pressing keys 0 to 9: for tablatures, it correspond
 to the fret number, for staffs, only 0 is used, and for tin whistles, the
 figure correspond to the number of closed holes on the flute (press a second
 time on the same key to obtain the octavo).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to select several notes by dragging the mouse.
 The + and - keys modify the selected notes' pitch; with staffs, it allows
 for sharps (#) and flats (b), and for tin whistles, half-holes.
 The 
\family sans
Note
\family default
 menu proposes several submenus for transposition or for rearranging the
 selected notes at a given fret number (for tablatures).
 To obtain additional lines above or below a stafs, simply move a note enough
 high or low with the + or - key.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Directional keys can be used for moving around in the partition; in Songwrite
 2, the horizontal distance is proportional to time.
 The current note duration is used by Songwrite 3 for determining the horizontal
 cusor speed, you may need to change the current duration for moving faster
 or slower.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notes' duration can be modified with the toolbar's buttons, the 
\family sans
Duration
\family default
 menu or the * (inscrease duration) and / (reduce duration) keys, however
 Songwrite 3 automatically adjust the note duration when you enter the next
 note (NB for some instruments that play several voice simultaneously, it
 can be problematic; in this case, it is possible to desactivate this behavious
 in the preferences).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Copy and paste
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Songwrite 3 uses a Linux-like copy-paste system: to copy a group of notes,
 select them.
 To move the selection, perform a drag-drop on one of the selected notes.
 Press Escape to cancel the drag drop.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To paste the notes selected previously, click the mouse middle button (usually
 the mouse roll).
 It is possible to adjust the exact pasting location by moving the mouse
 while keeping the middle button pressed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here again, Songwrite 3 uses the selected duration for aligning horizontally
 the pasted notes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Special effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Songwrite supports the following special effects: accentuation, hammer/pull/lega
to, slide, dead notes, bend, tremolo, roll, harmonic, fermata, appoggiatura
 and strumming directions.
 Special effects can be added using the toolbar, the keyboard shortcuts
 or the dialog box of the 
\family sans
Note
\family default
\SpecialChar \menuseparator

\family sans
Edit
\family default
 menu.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For effects that link two notes (hammers/pull/legato and slides), the effect
 must be set on the first note.
 For rolls, the effect should be set on the lower note of a chord (although
 it is still allowed to apply it to all the note of the chord, as needed
 in Songwrite 1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notes can gain new properties depending on their special effect, 
\emph on
e.g.

\emph default
 the bend pitch property for bends.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Restriction It is not possible to put more than one special effect of the
 same category on the same note.
\end_layout

